ss.org/Category_Templates\" target=\"_blank\">Codex</a> page, this is a pretty easy thing to do. My exhibits category, for example, simply has a new template file: <code>category-exhibits.php</code>. Similarly, Ryan Adams gets his own file too: <code>category-ryan-adams.php</code>.\n\nAfter you\'ve made a new template file, just copy the contents one of your other templates (<code>index.php</code> or <code>page.php</code>) and make changes as you need to. Wordpress happily takes care of the rest.','A Category for all seasons','','inherit','closed','closed','','390-autosave','','','2010-12-18 14:55:10','2010-12-18 18:25:10','',390,'http://waterstreetgm.org/2010/12/18/390-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(452,1,'2010-12-16 17:21:47','2010-12-16 20:51:47','You\'ll notice that this site has a few different sections or categories of content. The main frontpage blog posts, the (Rolling Stone quality) Ryan Adams reviews, seasonal exhibits, etc... Of course you don\'t want to have them all look the same, and of course you don\'t have to.\r\n\r\nAs per the <a title=\"WP Codex - Category templates\" href=\"http://codex.wordpress.org/Category_Templates\" target=\"_blank\">Codex</a> page, this is a pretty easy thing to do. My exhibits category, for example, simply has a new template file: <code>category-exhibits.php</code>. Similarly, Ryan Adams gets his own file too: <code>category-ryan-adams.php</code>.\r\n\r\nAfter you\'ve made a new template file, just copy the contents one of your other templates (<code>index.php</code> or <code>page.php</code>) and make changes as you need to. Wordpress happily takes care of the rest.','Style your categories differently','','inherit','closed','closed','','390-revision-5','','','2010-12-16 17:21:47','2010-12-16 20:51:47','',390,'http://waterstreetgm.org/2010/12/16/390-revision-5/',0,'revision','',0),(454,1,'2010-12-18 16:05:58','2010-12-18 19:35:58','Every good post needs a good byline.','Add a byline to your posts','','inherit','closed','closed','','453-revision','','','2010-12-18 16:05:58','2010-12-18 19:35:58','',453,'http://waterstreetgm.org/2010/12/18/453-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(455,1,'2010-12-18 16:33:44','2010-12-18 20:03:44','Every good post needs a good byline (the purple sub-heading above). With Wordpress, it\'s easy to setup:\n\n1. First things first, you need make a new custom field. This is right at the bottom of the <em>Add New Post </em>page.\n<a rel=\"attachment wp-att-456\" href=\"http://waterstreetgm.org/2010/12/18/add-a-byline-to-your-posts/custom-fields/\"><img class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-456\" title=\"custom-fields\" src=\"http://waterstreetgm.org/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/custom-fields-630x281.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"550\" height=\"245\" /></a>\n2. Next, add a little piece of code to the loop sections of the appropriate files in your theme (<code>single.php</code>, <code>index.php</code>, <code>single.php</code>, <code>page.php</code>, etc). Be sure to place this right before the &lt;code&gt;$the_content()&lt;/code&gt; function.\n\n[php]\n	&lt;?php if ( get_post_meta($post-&gt;ID, \'Byline\', true) ) : ?&gt;\n      &lt;div&gt; &lt;?php echo get_post_meta($post-&gt;ID, \'Byline\', true) ?&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\n    &lt;?php endif; ?&gt;\n	[/php]\n\nThis tells Wordpress to look for a <em>byline</em> before printing out the rest of the content in your post.\n\n3. Last, a little bit of CSS to make things look right and you\'re all set.\n\n[css]\n.byline {\n	font-size: 13px;\n	font-style: italic;\n	color: #CB1C9E;\n	margin-bottom: 25px;\n	}\n[/css]\n\nThis technique will work for any kind of custom content—just replace the word \'byline\' in the function above, with the name of your custom field.','Add a byline to your posts','','inherit','closed','closed','','453-autosave','','','2010-12-18 16:33:44','2010-12-18 20:03:44','',453,'http://waterstreetgm.org/2010/12/18/453-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(456,1,'2010-12-18 16:11:45','2010-12-18 19:41:45','','custom-fields','','in