tgm.org/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/drup.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(516,1,'2010-12-21 12:04:05','2010-12-21 15:34:05','','IMG_2838','','inherit','closed','closed','','img_2838-3','','','2010-12-21 12:04:05','2010-12-21 15:34:05','',0,'http://waterstreetgm.org/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/IMG_28381.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1219,1,'2011-01-26 16:55:29','2011-01-26 20:25:29','A brief chat with Matthew just highlighted something that might not be obvious to all WordPress users: Keeping pieces generic and reusable. WordPress has a pile of functions baked in to make it easy for you to get content out of your loops without having to do a lot of programming.   \n\nLet\'s use an example: linking your site’s name to the frontpage of your website. Of course this is something you’re already familiar with, just making a simple link to your domain name. As easy as writing <code><a href=”http://my-awesome-website.com”><h1 class=”site-name”>My Awesome Website</h1></a></code>. All we’ve done here is made our site name an H1, and linked it to our domain name. Paste that into the right spot in <code>header.php</code> and we’re done for the evening. \n\nBut there’s a better way. Next time, when you’re coding a site for a friend or client, you’ll need to change <code>http://my-awesome-website.com</code> to <code>http://another-mindless-website-for-corporate-america.com</code> manually. It’s not a big deal, but every second counts these days. Instead of baking the site name right into the header template file, use the WordPress function <code>bloginfo()</code> for guaranteed reusability. Like so: \n\n\nWill grab the name of your site.\n[php]\n&lt;h1&gt;&lt;?php bloginfo(\'name\'); ?&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;\n[/php] \n\nThis will grab the url of the homepage\n [php]\n&lt;?php php bloginfo(\'url\');  ?&gt;\n [/php] \n \nAnd finally, this will pull it all together and make the link work:\n[php]\n&lt;a href=&quot;&lt;?php bloginfo(\'url\'); ?&gt;&quot; title=&quot;&lt;?php bloginfo(\'name\'); ?&gt;&quot;&gt;&lt;?php bloginfo(\'name\'); ?&gt;&lt;/a&gt;\n[/php]\n\nStarting a new website or theme is a pain. You need to go through and setup the site name, the url, the contact info, etc, etc. If you use the built-in WordPress functions in your themes you\'ll save time and frustration down the road. Keeping as much of your themes as generic as possible will make them more reusable and make that first hour with a new theme a lot less of a chore.\n\nPs: There\'s a lot of other handy functions available for you to use.\n\n\n','Make your Wordpress themes reusable','','inherit','closed','closed','','1218-revision','','','2011-01-26 16:55:29','2011-01-26 20:25:29','',1218,'http://waterstreetgm.org/2011/01/26/1218-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(1218,1,'2011-01-26 17:05:27','2011-01-26 20:35:27','A brief chat with <a href=\"http://matthewbyrne.net\">Matthew</a> just highlighted something that might not be obvious to all WordPress users: why you want to keep theme pieces generic and reusable. WordPress has a pile of functions baked in to make it easy for you to get content out of your loops without having to do a lot of programming.   \r\n\r\nLet\'s use an example: linking your site’s name to the frontpage of your website. Of course this is something you’re already familiar with, just making a simple link to your domain name. \r\n\r\nIt\'s as easy as writing \r\n\r\n[php]\r\n&lt;a href=\'http://my-awesome-website.com\'&gt;&lt;h1&gt; My Awesome Website &lt;/h1&gt; &lt;/a&gt;\r\n[/php]\r\n\r\nAll we\'ve done here is made our site name an H1 and linked it to our domain name. Paste that into the right spot in <code>header.php</code> and we’re done for the evening. \r\n\r\nBut there’s a better way. Next time, when you’re coding a site for a friend or client, you’ll need to change <code>http://my-awesome-website.com</code> to <code>http://another-mindless-website-for-corporate-america.com</code> manually. It’s not a big deal, but every second counts these days. Instead of baking the site name right into the header template file, use the WordPress function <code>bloginfo()</code> for guaranteed reusability. Like so: \r\n\r\n\r\nThis will grab the name of your site:\r\n[php]\r\n&lt;h1&gt;&lt;?php bloginfo(\'name\'); ?&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;\r\n[/php] \r\n\r\nThis will get the url of the homepage:\r\n [php]\r\n&lt;?php php bloginfo(\'url\');  ?&gt;\r\n [/php] \r\n \r\nAnd finally, this will pull it all together and make the link work:\r\n[php]\r\n&lt;a href=&quot;&lt;?php bloginfo(\'url\'); ?&gt;&quot; title=&quot;&lt;?php bloginfo(\'name\'); ?&gt;&quot;&gt;&lt;?php bloginfo(\'name\'); ?&gt;&lt;/a&gt;\r\n[/php]\r\n\r\nAll that goodness came from just one single function, <code>bloginfo()</code>.\r\n\r\nStarting a new website or theme is a pain. You need to go through and setup the site name, the url, the contact info, etc, etc. If you use the built-in WordPress functions in your themes you\'ll save time and frustration down the road. Keeping as much of your themes as generic as possible will make them more reusable and make that first hour with a new theme a lot less of a chore.\r\n\r\nPs: There\'s a lot of other handy functions available for you to use. WordPress calls them <a href=\"http://codex.wordpress.org/Template_Tags\">Template Tags</a>. Happy theming.\r\n\r\n\r\n','Make your Wordpress themes reusable','','publish','closed','closed','','make-your-wordpress-themes-reusable','','','2011-01-26 17:05:27','2011-01-26 20:35:27','',0,'http://waterstreetgm.org/?p=1218',0,'post','',0),(1217,1,'2011-01-24 23:39:22','2011-01-25 03:09:22','After some recent criticism that brought to light the fact that this site was becoming \'somewhat\' Mac-centric, I decided to be more vigilant about spreading hatred and vitriol in the Windows direction. However, after helping a co-worker with a presentation on a Windows laptop today, I\'ve decided that only <em>more</em> hatred and vitriol are required, certainly not less.\r\n\r\nIn several years of using a Mac I have not seen a single screen look like the one attached. But yet, this was the first screen I saw this morning when I started the laptop. I must argue that (i) it makes absoltuely no sense to show this screen to my Grandmother, my Great Aunts, nor to <em>anyone</em> else, and (ii) there is no way a screen like this one would show up on a Mac.<a rel=\"attachment wp-att-866\" href=\"http://waterstreetgm.org/2010/10/15/on-macs-and-pcs-again/sshot20091217020232/\"><img class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-866\" title=\"Burning HELL, Windows style\" src=\"http://waterstreetgm.org/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/sshot20091217020232-550x259.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"525\" height=\"247\" /></a>\r\n\r\nDespite the abounding negativity from the naysayers about Apple these days, there\'s simply no way that a screen like this would be displayed to the user, and certainly you\'ll admit that it shouldn\'t.\r\n\r\nNo?','On Macs and PCs, again','','inherit','closed','closed','','294-revision-19','','','2011-01-24 23:39:22','2011-01-25 03:09:22','',294,'http://waterstreetgm.org/2011/01/24/294-revision-19/',0,'revision','',0),(1194,1,'2011-01-23 22:08:00','2011-01-24 01:38:00','Found some old Polaroids the other day while cleaning up my office. Taken with the x-ray gun-like <a href=\"http://www.photoethnography.com/ClassicCameras/MamiyaRB67.html\" target=\"_blank\">Mamiya RB67</a>.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-1189\" title=\"_MG_5201\" src=\"http://waterstreetgm.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/MG_5201-580x386.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"500\" />\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-1191\" title=\"_MG_5200\" src=\"http://waterstreetgm.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/MG_52001-580x386.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"500\" />','Some old Polaroids','','inherit','closed','closed','','1188-revision-3','','','2011-01-23 22:08:00','2011-01-24 01:38:00','',1188,'http://waterstreetgm.org/2011/01/23/1188-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(1195,1,'2011-01-23 22:10:26','2011-01-24 01:40:26','Found some old Polaroids the other day while cleaning up my office. Taken with the x-ray gun-like <a href=\"http://www.photoethnography.com/ClassicCameras/MamiyaRB67.html\" target=\"_blank\">Mamiya RB67</a>. If you\'ve never shot medium format film before, do yourself a favour and pick up a cheap camera and try it. A little grain goes a long way.\n\n<img class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-1189\" title=\"_MG_5201\" src=\"http://waterstreetgm.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/MG_5201-580x386.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"500\" />\n\n<img class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-1191\" title=\"_MG_5200\" src=\"http://waterstreetgm.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/MG_52001-580x386.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"500\" />','Some old Polaroids','','inherit','closed','closed','','1188-autosave','','','2011-01-23 22:10:26','2011-01-24 01:40:26','',1188,'http://waterstreetgm.org/2011/01/23/1188-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(1196,1,'2011-01-23 22:12:36','2011-01-24 01:42:36','How many Saturday <em>Globe and Mail</em>s do you let build up before you take a subscription break? 5? 6?\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-1197\" title=\"_MG_5199\" src=\"http://waterstreetgm.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/MG_5199-580x386.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"500\" />','Unread Globe and Mails','','publish','closed','closed','','unread-globe-and-mails','','','2011-01-23 22:13:31','2011-01-24 01:43:31','',0,'http://waterstreetgm.org/?p=1196',0,'post','',0),(1197,1,'2011-01-23 22:12:07','2011-01-24 01:42:07','','_MG_5199','','inherit','closed','closed','','_mg_5199','','','2011-01-23 22:12:07','2011-01-24 01:42:07','',1196,'http://waterstreetgm.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/MG_5199.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1198,1,'2011-01-23 22:11:55','2011-01-24 01:41:55','How many Globe\'s do you led build up before you take a subscription break? 5? 6?','Unread Globe and Mails','','inherit','closed','closed','','1196-revision','','','2011-01-23 22:11:55','2011-01-24 01:41:55','',1196,'http://waterstreetgm.org/2011/01/23/1196-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(1199,1,'2011-01-23 22:12:36','2011-01-24 01:42:36','How many Globe\'s do you led build up before you take a subscription break? 5? 6?\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-1197\" title=\"_MG_5199\" src=\"http://waterstreetgm.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/MG_5199-580x386.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"500\" />','Unread Globe and Mails','','inherit','closed','closed','','1196-revision-2','','','2011-01-23 22:12:36','2011-01-24 01:42:36','',1196,'http://waterstreetgm.org/2011/01/23/1196-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(1364,1,'2011-03-03 10:59:10','2011-03-03 14:29:10','My daily, after-work schedule has changed in the past month or so.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.thisamericanlife.org/\"><img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-1371\" title=\"tal______medium_image\" src=\"http://waterstreetgm.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/tal______medium_image.gif\" alt=\"\" width=\"200\" height=\"376\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<strong>Instead of:</strong>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Glass of wine</li>\r\n	<li>How was your day, honey?</li>\r\n	<li>Supper</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong>It now looks something like this:</strong>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Description of latest theme of <em>This American Life</em> podcast</li>\r\n	<li>Re-explanation of how <em>This American Life</em> podcast is organized (ie: it uses themes, and \'acts\' around these themes)</li>\r\n	<li>Glass of wine</li>\r\n	<li>Rundown of Act 1</li>\r\n	<li>Rundown of Act 2</li>\r\n	<li>Rundown of Act 3 (if exists)</li>\r\n	<li>[Typically longwinded] monologue about how these acts relate to the show\'s particular theme</li>\r\n	<li>Lengthy discussion and debate</li>\r\n	<li>How was your day, honey?</li>\r\n	<li>Supper</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<em><a href=\"http://www.thisamericanlife.org/\">This American Life</a></em> is a \'podcast\'. If you don\'t even know what a podcast is, that\'s ok. It is nothing more than a radio show where they tell stories. Some stories are happy, some are sad, some give explanations, some try and find them. The common bond holding these stories together is that they\'re all compelling and masterfully told. The \'podcast\' part is where you can download the radio show and play it on your computer or iPod. Hence the <em>pod</em>-part.\r\n\r\nAs I recently tweeted: if there\'s better radio out there, I haven\'t heard it. If you still haven\'t had a listen, please give it a try. Download a single podcast and just give yourself an hour to listen—I can almost guarantee that you\'ll be glad you did.','This American Life','','publish','closed','closed','','this-american-life','','','2011-03-03 11:01:02','2011-03-03 14:31:02','',0,'http://waterstreetgm.org/?p=1364',0,'post','',0),(1332,1,'2011-01-27 11:49:09','2011-01-27 15:19:09','I loathe few things in the world more than systems of hierarchal social structuring through ‘rites of passage’. You know what I’m talking about – the systems that make doctors work 70+ hour weeks during their training, or have nurses work night-shifts for the first 10 years of their career, or have teachers doing more volunteering in their first few years than teaching.\r\n\r\nThese systems live and breathe on collective memory and inherited suffering. <em>By God, if I had to work nights for 10 years, you’re going to work nights for 11, </em>and all that<em>.</em> These destructive systems feed each other and are kept alive through generations by surrounding them with the feeling that it is just a <em>rite of passage</em>, a long hallway you need to walk down before you reach the door to a better life. This is a terrible, soul-draining, self-perpetuating abomination of a system that serves to help no one. By the time people reach the door, they’ve only become bitter and resentful, and are more than happy to start doing it to someone else. But thanks to the web, there is a system that doesn’t work like this: design.\r\n\r\nDesign as Meritocracy\r\n\r\nA star is born every second on the web. Not just while riding a roller coaster on Youtube, and not just for being the first to start a Justin Beiber Fan Shrine. Every single day, brilliant new designers crawl out of their hibernation pit, stretch their arms, scratch their heads and upload designs and ideas that no one has thought of before. Most of these people literally come out of <em>nowhere</em>. They don’t need to know someone influential, nor live in Brooklyn, nor go to a leading graphic design school. They just need to do good work – no more or less than that.\r\n\r\nThe potential snowball that follows when something they’ve made gets picked up by Daring Fireball or Coudal or Dribbble or Zeldman (or …, or …, or…) could instantly lead to a productive and lucrative career working for some of the web’s biggest and best companies.\r\n\r\nExamples abound:\r\n\r\nWhen I first discovered Jessica Hiche, her website had only a small few illustrations on it – fantastic though they all were. Just two years (or less) later, she’s designing for <em>The New York Times Magazine, People Magazine, </em>and <em>The Boston Globe. </em>Not because of who she was connected to, nor because she spent years paying her dues (though she may have), but because she was producing unbelievably good work.\r\n\r\nCraig Mod is a designer I heard about only last year. After publishing <em>A GF1 Fieldtest,</em> a photo gallery/camera review from a trip to Nepal, he was launched into designer stardom. I might add at this point that he was living in <em>Tokyo</em> at the time. Can’t name one single other Tokyo-based designer? Exactly, neither can I. Craig’s new career was launched last year simply on the merits of his own good, hard work. From <em>Tokyo</em><em>.</em>\r\n\r\nPhotographer Jamie Beck came on the scene last year as well with a great new website, From me to You. Here, she’s simply posted photos 3-4 times a week of excerpts of shoots that she’s working on, or recipes, or friends’ apartments, or parks around NYC. Almost overnight she’s turned into a sensation, again because of what she’s done','Design as Meritocracy','','inherit','closed','closed','','1258-revision-3','','','2011-01-27 11:49:09','2011-01-27 15:19:09','',1258,'http://waterstreetgm.org/2011/01/27/1258-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(1201,1,'2011-01-23 22:14:45','2011-01-24 01:44:45','','_MG_5200','','inherit','closed','closed','','_mg_5200','','','2011-01-23 22:14:45','2011-01-24 01:44:45','',0,'http://waterstreetgm.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/MG_5200.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1204,1,'2011-01-24 19:47:05','2011-01-24 23:17:05','Rare January sunlight in St. John\'s.\r\n<img class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-1205\" title=\"IMG_3160\" src=\"http://waterstreetgm.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/IMG_3160-500x375.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /><img class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-1206\" title=\"IMG_3165\" src=\"http://waterstreetgm.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/IMG_3165-375x500.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"500\" />','January Sunlight','','publish','closed','closed','','january-sunlight','','','2011-01-24 19:50:52','2011-01-24 23:20:52','',0,'http://waterstreetgm.org/?p=1204',0,'post','',0),(1205,1,'2011-01-24 19:45:28','2011-01-24 23:15:28','','IMG_3160','','inherit','closed','closed','','img_3160','','','2011-01-24 19:45:28','2011-01-24 23:15:28','',1204,'http://waterstreetgm.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/IMG_3160.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1206,1,'2011-01-24 19:45:36','2011-01-24 23:15:36','','IMG_3165','','inherit','closed','closed','','img_3165','','','2011-01-24 19:45:36','2011-01-24 23:15:36','',1204,'http://waterstreetgm.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/IMG_3165.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1207,1,'2011-01-24 19:46:06','2011-01-24 23:16:06','<img class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-1205\" title=\"IMG_3160\" src=\"http://waterstreetgm.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/IMG_3160-500x375.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /><img class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-1206\" tit