,'<div id=\"_mcePaste\">A post from the <a href=\"http://37signals.com/svn/posts/2235-work-on-your-best-idea\" target=\"_blank\">37Signals blog</a> today hit me square in the stomach. Read for yourself if you wish, but here\'s the main idea:</div>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<div>Why would you want to pour so much of yourself into anything less than your best idea? Other ideas might seem more achievable or convenient, but if your heart and mind is elsewhere it’s all for naught.</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\">Whatever excuse you can come up with for why you’re settling for less is probably not good enough. It’s intensely draining to give up on your dreams and you’ll not look kindly back at yourself for threading water.</div></blockquote>\r\n<div>I had a long chat yesterday with a professor and coordinator of a graduate program at our university. We both wondered at length at why someone (me) would invest such a huge amount of time in a graduate program if that someone wasn\'t really interested in what was being studied. An excellent question, I thought. Our lack of answers for this specific question led us to a more general discussion of people in situations like mine - what he called the \"middle-class trap.\"</div>\r\n<div>The middle-class trap, as he described it, often found people like me having lots of education, various skills and abilities, and a reasonable amount of work experience - but having not even the faintest prevailing career direction. Our career indecision, he surmised, leads us into reasonably comfortable jobs that pay us enough to buy houses, cars and bi-annual vacations, but not quite enough to get <em>real</em> comfortable (you know, with savings accounts and children\'s education funds, and with, you know, job satisfaction).</div>','Threading Water','','draft','closed','closed','','','','','2011-05-23 20:33:29','2011-05-24 00:03:29','',0,'http://waterstreetgm.org/?p=758',0,'post','',0),(1095,1,'2011-01-10 16:12:15','2011-01-10 19:42:15','<div id=\"_mce