red in more ways than floors swept or coffees served.','','','inherit','closed','closed','','760-revision','','','2011-01-03 23:40:29','2011-01-04 03:10:29','',760,'http://waterstreetgm.org/2011/01/03/760-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(764,1,'2011-01-03 23:49:00','2011-01-04 03:19:00','<div id=\"_mcePaste\"><span style=\"font-family: Helvetica, Arial, Verdana, sans-serif; line-height: normal;\">\n<p style=\"margin-left: 4px; margin-right: 4px; line-height: 1.4em; margin-top: 4px;\">I\'ve been asked a few times in the past while about what I use for development, so I thought I\'d share.</p>\n\n<h3 style=\"margin-left: 4px; margin-right: 4px; line-height: 1.4em;\">Hardware</h3>\n<p style=\"margin-left: 4px; margin-right: 4px; line-height: 1.4em;\">I do all of my development on a July 09 Macbook Pro. At the office it\'s connected to a 22\" Dell monitor, while at home I just use it as is. One of these days I\'ll probably get an external monitor for home, but I\'m in no rush. The Macbook\'s screen is excellent and large enough for most of the work I do.</p>\n<p style=\"margin-left: 4px; margin-right: 4px; line-height: 1.4em;\">If I recall, it has 4GB of ram and a very large harddrive. Previous to this one, I had an \'05 or \'06 MBP with 2GB of RAM and a smaller harddrive. When I upgraded I thought I\'d be getting way more speed and performance, but I didn\'t. Truth is, the upgrade really wasn\'t much of an upgrade at all - but this is not a complaint. When you buy a Mac you buy a computer that should last you for a long time; it doesn\' tget bogged down by viruses and spyware and whatever else infects Windows machines. In short, I could be just as happy using my old MBP from 4-5 years ago.</p>\n\n<h3 style=\"margin-left: 4px; margin-right: 4px; line-height: 1.4em;\">Software</h3>\n<p style=\"margin-left: 4px; margin-right: 4px; line-height: 1.4em;\"><strong>Design</strong></p>\n<p style=\"margin-left: 4px; margin-right: 4px; line-height: 1.4em;\">I used to do all my design work in InDesign. All print work, all web mockups, all doodling, etc... everything used to be done in InDesign. I never liked Photoshop for doing web mockups, and I still don\'t use it. I find the layers concept necessary, but clunky and have always found it to be a hugely frustrating way to design for the web. I still use Photoshop from time to time, but am in the process of evaluating Pixelmator. Its really hard to adjust to a new program, even if the new one is good. Jury still out.</p>\n<p style=\"margin-left: 4px; margin-right: 4px; line-height: 1.4em;\">In past year I\'ve found that Apple\'s Keynote has replaced almost all of the others. Its currently where I do 90% of my print work, and about 99% of my web mockup work. Its so fast, so intuitive, and completely stays out of your way, and using master sheets allows you to work in the Photoshop layers paradigm. It has obvious limited capabilities, but given that do most of my real design work <a style=\"line-height: 1.4em;\" href=\"http://37signals.com/svn/posts/1061-why-we-skip-photoshop\">in the browser</a>, Keynote meets my needs perfectly.</p>\n<p style=\"margin-left: 4px; margin-right: 4px; line-height: 1.4em;\"><strong>Development</strong></p>\n<p style=\"margin-left: 4px; margin-right: 4px; line-height: 1.4em;\">After years using (and loathing) Dreamweaver, I\'ve long since switched to a plain text editor. I currently use (and love) Textmate along with the revolunitary Expandrive. First, Textmate is the very popular ultra-simple, yet feature-rich text editor for Mac. It has good code hilighting, is extremely lightweight, and is well ingrained in the Mac community.</p>\n<p style=\"margin-left: 4px; margin-right: 4px; line-height: 1.4em;\">Second, the day I discovered Expandrive was the day I realized how much (and why) I hated Dreamweaver. In just seconds, Expandrive helped me realize that Dreamweaver was an enormous, clunky, expensive piece of software that I was better off leaving behind. It had a place in the hot and sticky days of \"integrated development environments\" in 1998, but thankfully we\'ve seen the otherside of that non-sense.</p>\n<p style=\"margin-left: 4px; margin-right: 4px; line-height: 1.4em;\">Expandrive is basically FTP software with a twist: it treats your remote websites like external drives. Instead of maintaining a set of local and remote files and FTP-ing to and fro, you just mount your website as you would a thumbdrive and work away. To open a CSS file in Textmate, just drag it from the Finder window to the dock icon and you\'re good to go. Best of all, you can drag an entire website folder to the dock icon and open it as a \'project\' in Textmate.</p>\n<p style=\"margin-left: 4px; margin-right: 4px; line-height: 1.4em;\">Brilliant.</p>\n\n\n</span></div>','My Development Setup','','draft','closed','closed','','my-development-setup','','','2011-01-03 23:51:11','2011-01-04 03:21:11','',0,'http://waterstreetgm.org/?p=764',0,'post','',0),(763,1,'2011-01-03 23:42:10','2011-01-04 03:12:10','<div id=\"_mcePaste\">\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\">In the couple of years since I’ve worked at the hospital I’ve been watching a man in the cafeteria quickly climb the corporate ladder. When I first started, I remember seeing him going around emptying garbage bins, wheeling around a large, noisy, rickety gray plastic tub that he would take to the dumpster when full. Every few garbage bins, he would stop at a table and have a quick chat with someone he knew. Given that he knew someone at almost every table, the work was slow going.</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\"></div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\">A few months later I saw that he’d been upgraded to sweeper, where work primarily involved hours of pushing around a long, rectangular broom. Gaining a wider perimeter with his new task, he was running into way more people than before, and subsequently, getting less and less sweeping done.  Very soon after that he was bumped up again; this time he was serving coffee at