'closed','closed','','1137-revision','','','2011-01-10 22:26:55','2011-01-11 01:56:55','',1137,'http://waterstreetgm.org/2011/01/10/1137-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(1140,1,'2011-01-10 22:57:47','2011-01-11 02:27:47','','avatar','','inherit','closed','closed','','avatar','','','2011-01-10 22:57:47','2011-01-11 02:27:47','',2,'http://waterstreetgm.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/avatar.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1141,1,'2010-12-04 14:36:46','2010-12-04 14:36:46','<div id=\"_mcePaste\">\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\">\r\n<p class=\"p1\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><a rel=\"attachment wp-att-320\" href=\"http://waterstreetgm.org/2010/12/03/demolition/album-ryan-adams-demolition-2/\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-320 alignleft\" title=\"album-Ryan-Adams-Demolition\" src=\"http://waterstreetgm.org/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/album-Ryan-Adams-Demolition1-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" /></a>If I had just three words, they’d all be: DEMOLITION. It’s most certainly an avenue you need need need to go down. But march forward not in haste! This is not an album you put on while having a glass of wine, warming up the barbeque and waiting for the onions to go translucent in the frying pan on Saturday evening.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">If you could choose, and surely you can, the time to listen to this album for the first (good) time, to get it at its absolute best, is to wait until you’ve lost faith in almost everything. At the very least wait until you reach a point when you’re looking for clarity of some kind, for although you won’t find any here, it should be a moving experience while you look.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">At its peak, this album is a big dash of cream in a large black, bitter coffee of a day. A strangely uncomfortable, deflating-then-uplifting smack in the gob of a cd that will leave you worse than you felt when you started, and surely leave you wondering why on earth you ever put it on in the first pace. But my God, do put it on.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">The whole thing drips of October and Halloween and cool Fall air and lunchtime Anthropology seminars and the clocks going back.</p>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>','Demolition','','inherit','closed','closed','','270-revision-14','','','2010-12-04 14:36:46','2010-12-04 14:36:46','',270,'http://waterstreetgm.org/2010/12/04/270-revision-14/',0,'revision','',0),(1142,1,'2011-01-11 09:43:14','2011-01-11 13:13:14','<div id=\"_mcePaste\">\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\">\r\n<p class=\"p1\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><a rel=\"attachment wp-att-320\" href=\"http://waterstreetgm.org/2010/12/03/demolition/album-ryan-adams-demolition-2/\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-320 alignleft\" title=\"album-Ryan-Adams-Demolition\" src=\"http://waterstreetgm.org/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/album-Ryan-Adams-Demolition1-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" /></a>If I had just three words, they’d all be: DEMOLITION. It’s most certainly an avenue you need need need to go down. But march forward not in haste! This is not an album you put on while having a glass of wine, warming up the barbeque and waiting for the onions to go translucent in the frying pan on Saturday evening.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">If you could choose, and surely you can, the time to listen to this album for the first (good) time, to get it at its absolute best, is to wait until you’ve lost faith in almost everything. At the very least wait until you reach a point when you’re looking for clarity of some kind, for although you won’t find any here, it should be a moving experience while you look.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">At its peak, this album is a big dash of cream in a large black, bitter coffee of a day. A strangely uncomfortable, deflating-then-uplifting smack in the gob of a cd that will leave you worse than you felt when you started, and surely leave you wondering why on earth you ever put it on in the first pace. But my God, do put it on.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">The whole thing drips of October and Halloween, and of cool Fall air, and of lunchtime Anthropology seminars and the weekend when the clocks going back.</p>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>','Demolition','','inherit','closed','closed','','270-revision-15','','','2011-01-11 09:43:14','2011-01-11 13:13:14','',270,'http://waterstreetgm.org/2011/01/11/270-revision-15/',0,'revision','',0),(1143,1,'2011-01-11 09:48:50','0000-00-00 00:00:00','A nonsensical review of Neil Young\'s new CD in the Globe this past Saturday.  Absolutely filled completely meaningless language:\r\n \r\n\"There’s nothing in his lengthy discography quite like the last half of Walk With Me, the single that reached Canadian radio two weeks ago. From a deep, dense open chord, an almost arrhythmic swirl of sound carries scraps of Young’s vocals into remote octaves, scattering them across a thick mélange of sounds that finally subsides into a lilting, looping rhythm that’s like a hypnotically sped-up version of the main groove. It’s fresh and unexpected, yet it feels entirely organic.\"\r\naah......???\r\n\r\nAnd my absolute favorite paragraph from Neil himself: \r\n\r\n“We built dubs from pieces of the songs, from the tones and rhythm figures,” Young said. “We captured things, zoomed in on them, changed the octave they’re in, brought them to the front. But it’s all the same information, it’s all right there in the original song, the original performances.”\r\n\r\nWhat a pile of NON-SENSE!!!   What are \'dubs\'?  \'Tones\'? \'Rhythm figures\'? What is going on here.\r\n\r\nI know this is a controversial start to a stream of Friday emails, but it all simply serves to drive home my new opinion of Neil Young. I used to think that there was something there, that all those CDs I never got around to listening to had something on them that I needed to find.  But every time I went looking, I was left scratching my head: not only were 90% of the albums uninteresting, almost all of them were downright annoying to listen to.  Droning, stupidly melodic, inappropriately-minor-chord-strewn, vague lamentations about environmental discord.\r\n\r\nAnd finally, my new theory:  most of the love-in literature we read about Neil Young these days comes from people who write about their memories of Neil Young:  the time we went on that romanticized \'road-trip\' [fodder for another conversation], or the first time we took the kids to PEI, or the time we had that boil-up on the beach, or the time we went to that party down by Churchill Sq. after we wrote our last exam and we didn\'t know anyone there and we made up stories about who we were and we stayed up all night and that girl asked you to call her tomorrow and you said you would but you didn\'t.  Neil Young was right there for all of these events. Each and every one, he was there, sitting on a couch or a rock watching the fire and happily strumming his guitar. \r\n\r\nNeil Young isn\'t any good. [there!]  He just isn\'t. Neil Young is K-ROCK, Neil Young is Electric Lunch, he IS Oz-FM, he IS  Galaxy Canadian Rock Classics.   He\'s a collection of memories and ideals and dreams of Coleman stoves and eggs over easy and the smell of smoke on your coat the next morning. He\'s absolutely all of those things, but he surely he isn\'t good.  And I\'m starting to suspect that he never was. \r\n','Neil Young - Le Noise','','draft','closed','closed','','','','','2011-01-11 09:48:50','2011-01-11 13:18:50','',0,'http://waterstreetgm.org/?p=1143',0,'post','',0),(1144,1,'2011-01-11 09:47:56','2011-01-11 13:17:56','','Neil Young - Le Noise','','inherit','closed','closed','','1143-revision','','','2011-01-11 09:47:56','2011-01-11 13:17:56','',1143,'http://waterstreetgm.org/2011/01/11/1143-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(1145,1,'2011-01-11 09:48:00','2011-01-11 13:18:00','A nonsensical review of Neil Young\'s new CD in the Globe this past Saturday.  Completely meaningless language:','Neil Young - Le Noise','','inherit','closed','closed','','1143-revision-2','','','2011-01-11 09:48:00','2011-01-11 