es','','inherit','closed','closed','','1164-revision-7','','','2011-01-15 20:04:59','2011-01-15 23:34:59','',1164,'http://waterstreetgm.org/2011/01/15/1164-revision-7/',0,'revision','',0),(1175,1,'2011-01-15 20:09:12','2011-01-15 23:39:12','Custom Posts introduced in Wordpress 3.0 give you the ability to create more than just blog posts. You can now create separate post types for all your content—photos, recipes, labels from your uncles 8-Track collection—you know, anything you can think of. This involves just two steps: Making a new post type and displaying the new posts.\n\n<ol>\n	<li>First we need to tell WordPress about your new post type. Paste this into your <code>functions.php</code> file. If the file already has some code in there, omit the opening and closing PHP tags, if it doesn\'t leave them in. If your theme doesn\'t yet have a <code>functions.php</code> file, go ahead and make one. <code>Functions.php</code> should only have one set of opening and closing PHP tags.</li>\n	 [php] \n		&lt;?php\n			add_theme_support( \'menus\' );\n			add_action( \'init\', \'create_my_post_types\' );\n			function create_my_post_types() {\n				register_post_type( \'recipes\',\n					array(\n						\'labels\' =&gt; array(\n							\'name\' =&gt; __( \'Recipes\' ),\n							\'singular_name\' =&gt; __( \'Recipe\' )\n						),\n						\'public\' =&gt; true,\n					)\n				);\n			}\n		?&gt;	 \n	[/php] \n	 \n	\n	<li> Second (and last, whoot!) we want to display our new recipes for all the world to see, cook and enjoy. Paste this code anywhere you want to display your favourite recipes (may I recommend <code>sidebar.php</code>.</li>\n	\n	[php]\n	&lt;?php $loop = new WP_Query( array( \'post_type\' =&gt; \'recipes\', \'posts_per_page\' =&gt; 10 ) ); ?&gt;\n	&lt;?php while ( $loop-&gt;have_posts() ) : $loop-&gt;the_post(); ?&gt;\n\n	&lt;?php the_title( \'&lt;h2 class=&quot;entry-title&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;\' . get_permalink() . \'&quot; title=&quot;\' . the_title_attribute( \'echo=0\' ) . \'&quot; rel=&quot;bookmark&quot;&gt;\', \'&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;\' ); ?&gt;\n\n	&lt;div class=&quot;entry-content&quot;&gt;\n		&lt;?php the_content(); ?&gt;\n	&lt;/div&gt;\n	&lt;?php endwhile; ?&gt;\n	 \n[/php]\n\nLots of how-tos I\'ve found around the web show you how easy it is to create new posts, but few show you how to actually display them after. But now you\'re all set.\n\nHat-tip to Justin Tadlock for this and many more great WordPress tricks.\n\n \n ','Creating and Displaying custom post types','','inherit','closed','closed','','1164-revision-10','','','2011-01-15 20:09:12','2011-01-15 23:39:12','',1164,'http://waterstreetgm.org/2011/01/15/1164-revision-10/',0,'revision','',0),(1177,1,'2011-01-15 20:12:35','2011-01-15 23:42:35','Custom Posts introduced in Wordpress 3.0 give you the ability to create more than just blog posts. You can now create separate post types for all your content—photos, recipes, labels from your uncles 8-Track collection—you know, anything you can think of. This involves just two steps: Making a new post type and displaying the new posts.\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>First we need to tell WordPress about your new post type. Paste this into your <code>functions.php</code> file. If the file already has some code in there, omit the opening and closing PHP tags, if it doesn\'t leave them in. If your theme doesn\'t yet have a <code>functions.php</code> file, go ahead and make one. <code>Functions.php</code> should only have one set of opening and closing PHP tags.</li>\r\n	 [php] \r\n		&lt;?php\r\n			add_theme_support( \'menus\' );\r\n			add_action( \'init\', \'create_my_post_types\' );\r\n			function create_my_post_types() {\r\n				register_post_type( \'recipes\',\r\n					array(\r\n						\'labels\' =&gt; array(\r\n							\'name\' =&gt; __( \'Recipes\' ),\r\n							\'singular_name\' =&gt; __( \'Recipe\' )\r\n						),\r\n						\'public\' =&gt; true,\r\n					)\r\n				);\r\n			}\r\n		?&gt;	 \r\n	[/php] \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	<li> Second (and last, whoot!)