n, I was emailing all of my friends about it. If it was cool enough, they\'d email their friends and on it went. The same basic kind of communication was going on then as now. The only real difference being the ease with which something is now able to travel around—today\'s retweet is worth about 1,000 of yesterday\'s forwarded emails—but it\'s still the same thing.\r\n\r\nNone of the things that get thrown around today have anything to do with \'social media\'. They are merely tools that allow things to be shared easily, exactly the same as email did. Give a random person on the street a sketch pad and ask them to draw a picture of the internet for you and they\'re very, very likely to start drawing the Facebook logo. Ten years ago you would have been giving the sketch pad to someone who had just recently switched from a Terminal-based email reader like Pine and they would have drawn you a logo of Internet Explorer.\r\n\r\nIf you asked them what the internet actually was, they\'d probably just tell you that its simply a place with a huge pile of videos, pictures, Facebook-status-updates and weather forecasts. And none of that is any more social today than it was 10 years ago—it just gets around faster.','Un-social Media','','inherit','closed','closed','','1320-revision-10','','','2011-02-22 13:39:26','2011-02-22 17:09:26','',1320,'http://waterstreetgm.org/2011/02/22/1320-revision-10/',0,'revision','',0),(1333,1,'2011-02-23 16:49:47','2011-02-23 20:19:47','I loathe few things in the world more than systems of hierarchal social structuring through ‘rites of passage’. You know what I’m talking about – the systems that make doctors work 70+ hour weeks during their training, or have nurses work night-shifts for the first 10 years of their career, or have teachers doing more volunteering in their first few years than teaching.\r\n\r\nThese systems live and breathe on collective memory and inherited suffering. <em>By God, if I had to work nights for 10 years, you’re going to work nights for 11, </em>and all that<em>.</em> These destructive systems feed each other and are kept alive through generations by surrounding them with the feeling that it is just a <em>rite of passage</em>, a long hallway you need to walk down before you reach the door to a better life. This is a terrible, soul-draining, self-perpetuating abomination of a system that serves to help no one. By the time people reach the door, they’ve only become bitter and resentful, and are more than happy to start doing it to someone else. But thanks to the web, there is a system that doesn’t work like this: design.\r\n\r\nDesign as Meritocracy\r\n\r\nA star is born every second on the web. Not just while riding a roller coaster on Youtube, and not just for being the first to start a Justin Beiber Fan Shrine. Every single day, brilliant new designers crawl out of their hibernation pit, stretch their arms, scratch their heads and upload designs and ideas that no one has thought of before. Most of these people literally come out of <em>nowhere</em>. They don’t need to know someone influential, nor live in Brooklyn, nor go to a leading graphic design school. They just need to do good work – no more or less than that.\r\n\r\nThe potential snowball that follows when something they’ve made gets picked up by Daring Fireball or Coudal or Dribbble or Zeldman (or …, or …, or…) could instantly lead to a productive and lucrative career working for some of the web’s biggest and best companies.\r\n\r\nExamples abound:\r\n\r\nWhen I first discovered Jessica Hiche, her website had only a small few illustrations on it – fantastic though they all were. Just two years (or less) later, she’s designing for <em>The New York Times Magazine, People Magazine, </em>and <em>The Boston Globe. </em>Not because of who she was connected to, nor because she spent years paying her dues (though she may have), but because she was producing unbelievably good work.\r\n\r\nCraig Mod is a designer I heard about only last year. After publishing <em>A GF1 Fieldtest,</em> a photo gallery/camera review from a trip to Nepal, he was launched into designer stardom. I might add at this point that he was living in <em>Tokyo</em> at the time. Can’t name one single other Tokyo-based designer? Exactly, neither can I. Craig’s new career was launched last year simply on the merits of his own good, hard work. From <em>Tokyo</em><em>.</em>\r\n\r\nPhotographer Jamie Beck came on the scene last year as well with a great new website, From me to You. Here, she’s simply posted photos 3-4 times a week of excerpts of shoots that she’s working on, or recipes, or friends’ apartments, or parks around NYC. Almost overnight she’s turned into a sensation, again because of what she’s done','Design as Meritocracy','','inherit','closed','closed','','1258-revision-4','','','2011-02-23 16:49:47','2011-02-23 20:19:47','',1258,'http://waterstreetgm.org/2011/02/23/1258-revision-4/',0,'revision','',0),(1334,1,'2011-02-23 16:57:10','2011-02-23 20:27:10','I\'ve thought a lot about this, and I think it\'s finally time that we develop some sort of oath-swearing ceremony for new and established web designers. I think that the attached covers most of the major points fairly well.\n\n<em>* Please note: In the absence of sworn, legal officials, this oath </em>\n\nA web designers oath\n\nI solemnly swear to follow web standards, to not use custom, half-baked frameworks instead of open source tools, use CSS instead of tables, Flash instead of jQuery, Times New Roman instead of Georgia, and will absolutely refuse to make a website for a wedding photographer or restaurant owner that full-screens and plays [bad] music.\n\nSincerely,','A Web Designers Oath','','inherit','closed','closed','','1150-revision-2','','','2011-02-23 16:57:10','2011-02-23 20:27:10','',1150,'http://waterstreetgm.org/2011/02/23/1150-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(1335,1,'2011-02-23 16:58:10','2011-02-23 20:28:10','I\'ve thought a lot about this, and 