0-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(1755,1,'2011-05-31 08:40:49','2011-05-31 12:10:49','Currently addicted to the Dixie Chicks <em><a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UtqwL-ZPhAA&amp;feature=related\" target=\"_blank\">Long Way Around</a></em>. Don\'t judge me.','Dixie Chicks Long Way Around','','publish','closed','closed','','ixie-chicks-long-way-around','','','2011-05-31 09:56:41','2011-05-31 13:26:41','',0,'http://waterstreetgm.org/?p=1755',0,'post','',0),(1756,1,'2011-05-31 08:40:49','2011-05-31 12:10:49','','ixie Chicks Long Way Around','','inherit','closed','closed','','1755-revision','','','2011-05-31 08:40:49','2011-05-31 12:10:49','',1755,'http://waterstreetgm.org/2011/05/31/1755-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(1757,1,'2011-05-31 08:57:07','2011-05-31 12:27:07','MaxVoltar on making <a href=\"http://maxvoltar.com/archive/i-want-to-write-more\" target=\"_blank\">excuses for not writing more</a>. Happy that someone has finally written down what we all feel.','MaxVoltar on making excuses for not writing more','','publish','closed','closed','','maxvoltar-on-making-excuses-for-not-writing-more','','','2011-05-31 08:57:07','2011-05-31 12:27:07','',0,'http://waterstreetgm.org/?p=1757',0,'post','',0),(1758,1,'2011-05-31 08:57:07','2011-05-31 12:27:07','','MaxVoltar on making excuses for not writing more','','inherit','closed','closed','','1757-revision','','','2011-05-31 08:57:07','2011-05-31 12:27:07','',1757,'http://waterstreetgm.org/2011/05/31/1757-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(1910,1,'2011-06-20 15:31:00','0000-00-00 00:00:00','There’s at least 1,000 articles out there aimed at helping you become a better web designer: Be a better coder, a better designer, a better Photoshopper, a better illustrator, etc. But there’s only <em>one lonesome article</em> out there designed to help you actually make money while doing it.\r\n\r\nI’ve been making websites now for about 7-8 years. I’ve read books, blogs, listened to podcasts, interviews, watched videos, tutorials, you name it. In this time, I’ve tried to stay current, tried to learn new things, be ready to experiment with any kind of new technology that seemed like it might be useful. In all this time I’ve probably consumed thousands of pieces of content aimed to make me a better, more versatile web designer.\r\n\r\nI have spent time learning: HTML, CSS, PHP, ASP, Javascript, Flash, Photoshop, Illustrator, WordPress, Drupal, Joomla, HTML5, CSS3, Ruby on Rails, jQuery, Prototype, and likely many others I’ve forgotten. You probably have as well. But did you notice anything missing on that list? Of course you did: How the hell are you supposed to actually make money doing this?\r\n<h2>Income, an industry’s dirty little secret</h2>\r\nNoah Stokes wrote the <a href=\"http://esbueno.noahstokes.com/post/3200424757/the-magic-spreadsheet-or-lets-talk-about-money\" target=\"_blank\">one single article</a> I’m talking about. In it, he provides a spreadsheet for you fill in to see what could happen to your revenues if you added an employee or two. The article doesn’t cover what you might charge, what an average income might look like, how you get more business, etc, but does a good job arguing its single point—extra employees could mean extra revenue.\r\n\r\nIt really is bizarre that I’ve been able to read/consume literally thousands of pieces of professional development content, but have read just a single, measly article about the business end of things. Sure, anyone would rather watch a video about making a <a href=\"http://methodandcraft.com/videos/unique-vector-shapes-in-illustrator\" target=\"_blank\">retro-style logo</a> in Illustrator than read a business article, but at some point we all need to think about money.\r\n\r\nHere, for example, are some sample questions that you won’t find answers for online:\r\n1.	How much should I charge for a blog redesign?\r\n2.	How much for a small business website?\r\n3.	How many hours should it take?\r\n4.	How much should I charge to move something from Drupal to WordPress?\r\n5.	What’s an average rate for a graphic designer? For an illustrator?\r\n6.	My server is crashing. How much would it cost to have a sysadmin look at it?\r\n7.	How much should I charge for a logo?\r\n8.	Should I charge non-profits less?\r\n9.	How/where do I advertise? How much should I invest in advertising?\r\n10.	Do I need to start by working for free to build a portfolio?\r\n\r\nEtc, etc, etc. You won’t find reliable answers to any of these basic questions online (except the last one). Go try and find them.\r\n<h2>A more realistic spreadsheet?</h2>\r\n<img class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-1919\" title=\"freelance-economics\" src=\"http://waterstreetgm.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/freelance-economics-500x375.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" />\r\n\r\nJust have a quick look at the spreadsheet I put together and see if the numbers make sense for the work you do. It was designed for freelancers (people like me and probably you) without employees. Could you make a living from either of four categories? Could you realistically do 26 projects a year? Could you handle 5 projects with budgets larger than $5,000? Would anyone in the town where you work actually pay $5,000 for a website?  Or is $5,000 an entry-level project for you? Would a company trust their $8,000 project with a freelancer?\r\n\r\nThe spreadsheet I present here is a fairly bleak one: Either you complete a small-ish website every two weeks for $1,600, or you do a large-ish website every month for $5,000+. In both situations, you’re not left with a huge sum of money for what would be a large pile of work over the course of a year. Remember, I haven’t factored in income tax, health insurance, retirement savings, or anything else to whittle away at your potential $88,400 annual income. When you factor in all those deductions, you’ll be left with about $55-60,000—hardly putting you on easy street.\r\n\r\nPlease download the spreadsheet and have a look. Fill in your own numbers and see what you come up with. If you already work full-time and just freelance in the evenings, put those numbers in—maybe you’ll work on just 6-8 projects this year at $1,500 a piece—how do those numbers look?\r\n\r\nThe second worksheet shows my current and ideal numbers. I work full-time and am only interested in some evening work. To get to the income I’d like, I’d need to do quite a few more projects, and charge more for each one. I’m still a bit unsure if that’s possible or not.\r\n\r\nThis exercise has proven very useful for me: I’d often wondered in the past about fulltime freelancing, but after putting together this spreadsheet, I can’t imagine how I’d be able to survive.\r\n<h2>Footnotes</h2>\r\nI’m not going to finish this article without some concrete numbers. For reference, I charge $40 an hour and would charge about $1,500-2,000 for what I consider to be a small website (a blog redesign, a website for a small business, a band or a photographer, etc). A medium website would have a little more complexity – a complete rebranding, different content types, lots of custom views and queries, custom taxonomies, content migration, content creation (writing/editing), etc, and would run into at least $3-5,000.','The Economics of Freelance web design','','draft','closed','closed','','','','','2011-06-20 15:31:00','2011-06-20 19:01:00','',0,'http://waterstreetgm.org/?p=1910',0,'post','',0),(1760,1,'2011-05-31 08:40:49','2011-05-31 12:10:49','Currently addicted to the Dixie Chicks <em><a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UtqwL-ZPhAA&amp;feature=related\" target=\"_blank\">Long Way Around</a></em>. Don\'t judge me.','ixie Chicks Long Way Around','','inherit','closed','closed','','1755-revision-2','','','2011-05-31 08:40:49','2011-05-31 12:10:49','',1755,'http://waterstreetgm.org/2011/05/31/1755-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(2101,1,'2011-09-10 08:56:49','2011-09-10 12:26:49','<blockquote>Well, you don’t want to show something that is weak, or poor, so you want to hold off until you get it right. And the trick is to actually stop that behavior. We show it every day, when it’s incomplete. If everybody does it, every day, then you get over the embarrassment. And when you get over the embarrassment, you’re more creative.</blockquote>\n—<a href=\"http://blog.protoshare.com/2011/04/getting-over-embarrassment-and-getting-done\" target=\"_blank\">Ed Catmull</a>, Pixar President','Getting over the embarrassment of incomplete design','','inherit','closed','closed','','2099-autosave','','','2011-09-10 08:56:49','2011-09-10 12:26:49','',2099,'http://waterstreetgm.org/2011/09/10/2099-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(1763,1,'2011-05-31 10:34:51','2011-05-31 14:04:51','A stunning, if headache-inspiring map of the railway system around Tokyo.\r\n \r\n<a href=\"http://zeroperzero.com/crs/tokyo-.html\"><img src=\"http://waterstreetgm.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/tokyo-r2-500x330.jpg\" alt=\"\" title=\"tokyo-r2\" width=\"500\" height=\"330\" class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-1764\" /></a>\r\n\r\n\r\n—via <a href=\"http://zeroperzero.com/crs/tokyo-.html\">Zeroperzero</a>','Tokyo Railway System Map','A stunning, if headache-inspiring map of the railway system around Tokyo.\r\n \r\n<a href=\"http://zeroperzero.com/crs/tokyo-.html\"><img src=\"http://waterstreetgm.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/tokyo-r2-500x330.jpg\" alt=\"\" title=\"tokyo-r2\" width=\"500\" height=\"330\" class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-1764\" /></a>\r\n\r\n—via <a href=\"http://zeroperzero.com/crs/tokyo-.html\">Zeroperzero</a>','publish','closed','closed','','tokyo-railway-system-map','','','2011-06-05 10:56:24','2011-06-05 14:26:24','',0,'http://waterstreetgm.org/?p=1763',0,'post','',0),(1764,1,'2011-05-31 10:34:17','2011-05-31 14:04:17','','tokyo-r2','','inherit','closed','closed','','tokyo-r2','','','2011-05-31 10:34:17','2011-05-31 14:04:17','',1763,'http://waterstreetgm.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/tokyo-r2.jpg',0,'attachment','image/j